<div id="review_479730853" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/479730853" />
    <a title="Sashi" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1782401-sashi"><img alt="Sashi" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1334066353p2/1782401.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/479730853?book_show_action=true">Dec 17, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sashi" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sashi" href="/user/show/1782401-sashi">Sashi</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer479730853" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8442429301469764889">First of all, I do not know what relevance the title has to the story. However, a very well written story, sometimes funny, mostly poignant, tale of a small child orphaned in Canada. Her mother was Indian who&apos;s family severed all ties with when she married a Canadian. Now the grandfather is the legal guardian for the child and how the child copes with new life in India and how he copes with a new grandchild is the story. <br/>The Indian life is perfectly depicted. The librarian who whets the books he</span>
  <span id="freeText8442429301469764889" style="display:none">First of all, I do not know what relevance the title has to the story. However, a very well written story, sometimes funny, mostly poignant, tale of a small child orphaned in Canada. Her mother was Indian who's family severed all ties with when she married a Canadian. Now the grandfather is the legal guardian for the child and how the child copes with new life in India and how he copes with a new grandchild is the story. <br />The Indian life is perfectly depicted. The librarian who whets the books her customers take (Cherry Nurse Betty is not a book on Medicine, sir.), the romance between the milkman and the 42 year old brahmin spinster, the relationship between an old crone and her son and daughter-in-law, the reluctance of this woman to get her old daughter married using some excuse or other, the literal translations sometimes (what-what things, simply-simply, )are all cute. Simple friendhsips, mountainous responsibilities, frustrations of underachievement and betrayal are all understandable to me. I wonder how a western mind thought about it however. Would be worth discussing.<br />The father of the main character seems a horrendous beast--making the poor boy learn all that he can in an encycolpedia when he is 8years old! The child Nandana is a very lovable child. Her thoughts that resonate with "No WAY" in her mind, her thinking of the grandmother as "Mamma lady", her missing her parents (her Canadian father seemed such a wonderful parent) are all well laid out. All in all, excellent. </span>
  <a data-text-id="8442429301469764889" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


